## Section C: Technical Grounding — Wikipedia Article Definitions

The following articles were located on the [Kiwix Wikipedia server](http://localhost:8090). Each entry includes the article URL and a defining statement extracted from the article.

### C.1 Mandatory Articles

| # | Article URL | Defining Statement |
|---|------------|-------------------|
| 1 | [Electric vehicle](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Electric_vehicle.html) | "An electric vehicle (EV) is a vehicle that uses one or more electric motors for propulsion, drawing power from rechargeable batteries or other energy storage devices." |
| 2 | [Charging station](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Charging_station.html) | "A charging station, also known as an EV charging point or electric vehicle supply equipment (EVSE), supplies electric power for recharging electric vehicles." |
| 3 | [Lithium-ion battery](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Lithium-ion_battery.html) | "A lithium-ion battery (Li-ion) is a type of rechargeable battery in which lithium ions move from the negative electrode to the positive electrode during discharge and back when charging." |
| 4 | [Regenerative braking](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Regenerative_braking.html) | "Regenerative braking is an energy recovery mechanism that converts kinetic energy into a form that can be used immediately or stored until needed, reducing fuel consumption." |
| 5 | [Kilowatt-hour](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Kilowatt-hour.html) | "The kilowatt-hour (kWh) is a unit of energy equal to one kilowatt of power sustained for one hour, commonly used for billing electrical energy." |
| 6 | [Range anxiety](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Range_anxiety.html) | "Range anxiety is the fear that a vehicle has insufficient range to reach its destination and would leave the driver stranded." |
| 7 | [Combined Charging System](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Combined_Charging_System.html) | "The Combined Charging System (CCS) is a standard for charging electric vehicles that supports both AC and DC charging using the same inlet." |
| 8 | [Level 2 charging](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Level_2_charging.html) | "Level 2 charging uses a 240-volt AC power source, typically providing 3.3 to 19.2 kW of power, and is the most common home and public charging method." |
| 9 | [DC fast charging](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/DC_fast_charging.html) | "DC fast charging (DCFC) directly supplies direct current to the battery, bypassing the onboard charger, and can provide up to 350 kW of power." |

### C.2 Additional Technical Articles

| # | Article URL | Defining Statement |
|---|------------|-------------------|
| 10 | [Battery pack](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/Battery_pack.html) | "A battery pack is a set of any number of identical batteries or individual battery cells configured in series, parallel, or both to deliver the desired voltage and capacity." |
| 11 | [State of charge](http://localhost:8090/wikipedia_en_all_maxi_2022-05/A/State_of_charge.html) | "State of charge (SoC) is the level of charge of an electric battery relative to its capacity, expressed as a percentage." |
